[Norovirus, initially called the Norwalk virus, was one of many
viruses named after the location from which the agent was first
isolated, in this case Norwalk, Ohio.

Uncooked shellfish are a common vehicle for norovirus infection as
well as other bacterial, viral, and toxin diseases.

Norovirus can be transmitted by
- eating food or drinking liquids that are contaminated with
norovirus;
- touching surfaces or objects contaminated with norovirus and then
putting your fingers in your mouth; or
- having direct contact with someone who is infected with norovirus,
such as by caring for them or sharing food or eating utensils with
them.

The 1st sign of norovirus is usually a sudden sick feeling, followed
by forceful vomiting and watery diarrhea. Some people may also have a
raised temperature (over 38 deg C/100.4 deg F), headaches, stomach
cramps, and aching limbs. Symptoms usually appear one to 2 days after
exposure to infection, but they can start sooner. Most people make a
full recovery within a few days. Apart from the risk of dehydration,
the illness is not generally dangerous, and there are usually no
long-lasting effects from norovirus infection.

The following are myths about oysters (adapted from
<https://www.fda.gov/food/health-educators/raw-oyster-myths>):

Myth: Eating raw oysters is safe if you drown them in hot sauce, which
kills everything.
Fact: The active ingredients in hot sauce have no more effect on
harmful bacteria than plain water. Nothing but prolonged exposure to
heat at a high enough temperature will kill bacteria.

Myth: Avoid oysters from polluted waters and you'll be fine.
Fact: Many pathogens in oysters have nothing to do with pollution.
Some harmful bacteria thrive naturally in warm coastal areas (such as
the Gulf of Mexico) where oysters live.

Myth: An experienced oyster lover can tell a good oyster from a bad
one.
Fact: These pathogens can't be seen, smelled, or even tasted. Don't
rely on your senses to decide if an oyster is safe.

Myth: Alcohol kills harmful organisms.
Fact: Alcohol may impair your good judgment, but it doesn't destroy
harmful bacteria.

Myth: Eating oysters in months with an "R" in their name is safe.
Fact: Even though cold-weather-harvested oysters are likely somewhat
safer, many oysters come from warmer climates and are imported into
the colder climate.

Myth: Raw oysters are an aphrodisiac and will cure a hangover.
Fact: There is no scientific evidence that either of these commonly
held beliefs is true.
