nal.com/food-poisoning-information/oyster-norovirus-outbreak-hits-191-in-lo=
s-angeles-and-san-diego/</a>=0D<br>=0D<br>=0D<br>The Los Angeles County Dep=
artment of Public Health is reporting that<br>there are more than 150 suspe=
cted local cases of gastrointestinal<br>illness linked to the consumption o=
f raw oysters, likely caused by<br>norovirus. At this time, Public Health i=
s warning consumers not to eat<br>raw oysters from Laguna De Guerrero Negro=
, Baja California, Mexico;<br>Laguna Manuela, Baja California, Mexico; and =
Bahia Salina, Sonora,<br>Mexico, because they may be linked to outbreaks of=
 norovirus illnesses<br>in California. Before eating raw oysters, consumers=
 should ask the<br>vendor/restaurant where the oysters were harvested.=0D<b=
r>=0D<br>Public Health is currently working with the California Department =
of<br>Public Health (CDPH) to investigate and confirm the source of this<br=
>cluster of gastrointestinal illness cases. If you believe that you<br>beca=
me sick from eating or drinking something, please file a report.=0D<br>=0D<=
br>San Diego County health officials have linked 41 confirmed and<br>probab=
le cases=E2=80=AFof norovirus=E2=80=AFillness to raw=E2=80=AFoysters=E2=80=
=AFimported<br>from a specific harvest location in Northwest Mexico.=0D<br>=0D=
<br>The FDA is warning restaurants and food retailers in California that<br=
>have recently purchased oysters from Sociedad Acuicola GolPac (MX 06<br>SP=
) harvested from Bahia Salina, Sonora, Mexico, on 18 Dec or 27 Dec<br>2023.=
 The FDA alert is also for consumers in California who have<br>recently con=
sumed oysters in San Diego or Los Angeles County<br>restaurants sourced fro=
m Sociedad Acuicola GolPac (MX 06 SP) harvested<br>from Bahia Salina, Sonor=
a, Mexico, on 18 Dec or 27 Dec 2023.=0D<br>=0D<br>The FDA is advising resta=
urants and food retailers not to serve or<br>sell and to dispose of oysters=
 and consumers not to eat oysters from<br>Sociedad Acuicola GolPac (MX 06 S=
P) harvested from Bahia Salina,<br>Sonora, Mexico, on 18 Dec or 27 Dec 2023=
 because they may be<br>contaminated with norovirus.=0D<br>=0D<br>Oysters c=
ontaminated with norovirus can cause illness if eaten raw,<br>and potential=
ly severe illness in people with compromised immune<br>systems. Food contai=
ning norovirus may look, smell, and taste normal.<br>Consumers of these pro=
ducts experiencing symptoms of illness should<br>contact their healthcare p=
rovider and report their symptoms to their<br>local health department. Diar=
rhea, abdominal cramps, nausea, vomiting,<br>and fever may be associated wi=
th gastroenteritis infections caused by<br>this organism.=0D<br>=0D<br>Peop=
le of all ages can get infected and sick with norovirus. The most<br>common=
 symptoms of norovirus are diarrhea, vomiting, nausea, and<br>stomach pain.=
 Other symptoms include fever, headache, and body aches.<br>A person usuall=
y develops symptoms 12 to 48 hours after exposure to<br>norovirus. Most peo=
ple with norovirus illness get better within one to<br>3 days.=0D<br>=0D<br=
>[Byline: Patti Waller]=0D<br>=0D<br>--=0D<br>Communicated by:=0D<br>ProMED=
<br><br>[Norovirus, initially called the Norwalk virus, was one of many<br>=
viruses named after the location from which the agent was first<br>isolated=
, in this case Norwalk, Ohio.=0D<br>=0D<br>Uncooked shellfish are a common =
vehicle for norovirus infection as<br>well as other bacterial, viral, and t=
oxin diseases.=0D<br>=0D<br>Norovirus can be transmitted by=0D<br>- eating =
food or drinking liquids that are contaminated with<br>norovirus;=0D<br>- t=
ouching surfaces or objects contaminated with norovirus and then<br>putting=
 your fingers in your mouth; or=0D<br>- having direct contact with someone =
who is infected with norovirus,<br>such as by caring for them or sharing fo=
od or eating utensils with<br>them.=0D<br>=0D<br>The 1st sign of norovirus =
is usually a sudden sick feeling, followed<br>by forceful vomiting and wate=
ry diarrhea. Some people may also have a<br>raised temperature (over 38 deg=
 C/100.4 deg F), headaches, stomach<br>cramps, and aching limbs. Symptoms u=
sually appear one to 2 days after<br>exposure to infection, but they can st=
art sooner. Most people make a<br>full recovery within a few days. Apart fr=
om the risk of dehydration,<br>the illness is not generally dangerous, and =
there are usually no<br>long-lasting effects from norovirus infection.=0D<b=
